ns:common.topic.description: SETL2 is a backwards incompatible descendant of the SETL programming language created by Kirk Snyder of the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences at New York University in the late 1980s. Like its predecessor, it is based on the theory and notation of finite sets, but has also been influenced in syntax and style by the Ada programming language.
